{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489499"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:18:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:18:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"673"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/673"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.05,0.64,0.2,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"673"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82669"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/673"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"673"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67815"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"623"},{"type":"tags","id":"6253"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1218"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1552"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28274"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82669"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of cough productive of purulent sputum. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is a lifelong non-smoker and works as an accountant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals bilateral basal crepitations. Chest x-ray is shown below (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fine needle aspiration biopsy","Positron emission tomography scan","Computed tomography of chest and abdomen","Bronchoscopy","Respiratory function test"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with multiple rounded pulmonary nodules on chest X-ray, which is highly suspicious for metastatic disease. The initial investigation of choice is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomputed tomography of chest and abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E to better characterise the lung lesions and identify a potential primary malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E may eventually be required for tissue diagnosis, but CT imaging should be performed first to guide the most appropriate biopsy site and ensure the procedure can be performed safely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositron emission tomography scan\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for staging known malignancy and detecting distant metastases, but is not the most appropriate next investigation before CT has been performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated for centrally located lesions or endobronchial disease, but CT imaging should be obtained first to determine if bronchoscopy would be useful and guide the procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespiratory function test\u003C/strong\u003E would not help diagnose or characterise the pulmonary nodules seen on chest X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon primary tumours that metastasise to the lungs include colorectal, breast, renal, and head/neck cancers. These typically spread via haematogenous or lymphatic routes. A systematic approach starting with CT imaging allows for appropriate characterisation of the lesions and guides subsequent investigation and management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multiple pulmonary nodules on chest X-ray are highly suspicious for metastatic disease.","CT chest and abdomen is the most appropriate initial investigation to characterise pulmonary nodules and identify a potential primary malignancy.","Common primary tumours that metastasise to lungs include colorectal, breast, renal and head/neck cancers."],"references":["Jamil A, Kasi A. Lung Metastasis.  StatPearls. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing Copyright \u00a9 2020, StatPearls Publishing LLC.; 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67815"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"673"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18666"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18666"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c87f37c3-dc1d-4769-af40-7e8b3ab10b77.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c87f37c3-dc1d-4769-af40-7e8b3ab10b77.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":330,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67815"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T19:27:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T19:28:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"673"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82669"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},